<h2><a>Starting to Code in Kindergarten
  <br>
  <span class="subtitle">Learning Programming Logic</span></a></h2>
<a href="http://imgur.com/h0qS4Bv"><img src="http://i.imgur.com/h0qS4Bv.png?1"></a>
	<!--For example, is this an introductory activity? A game? A tutorial? A project? A practical activity? Giving a brief description of the type of activity will help others quickly understand what this resource is.-->
    <h3>The Big Picture: Getting to Know Code</h3>

  	<!--Give 2 to 3 sentences about what the activity is and what learners will do.-->
    <p>Students will explore and learn what code can look like, how to create physical coding blocks, and how to use them to creat their own basic programs. <br>
    </p>


  <h3>Steps:</h3>
 <ol>
   <li> <!-- 
     Explain each step of the activity so that others can repeat it in their learning situations. Replace the example text and find images that help you explain your steps!-->
     <p>An introductory activity gets the blood pumping, forms connections between learners, and introduces a topic. There are thousands of different ways to introduce a topic and get learners interacting with each other. Choose one and hack it to be your own!</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>A good second activity is one that gives pointed instruction to participants on tools or procedures. An example would be allowing the participants to get used to the interface of Thimble or Popcorn by having them make projects. Before learners can practically apply new skills, they need to be comfortable with the tools they'll be using and have a basic understanding of the skills they'll be sharpening.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>A practical, project based activity allows learners to delve deeper into the essential questions of your session. Go back to thinking of the results: what will your learners MAKE when they are done? What research do they need to do? What text, images, videos, sound clips do they need to gather? </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>Make sure and find or create any resources your learners might need on creating content. Create a project that gives learners enough time to explore and tinker while working towards the completion of the activity.</p>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Materials:</h3>
<ul>
  <li><em>What is needed to run this activity?</em></li>
	<li><em>What other resources or links are helpful for mentors?</em></li>

  </ul>
  <h3>Discussion:</h3>
  <li><em>List your questions here! </em></li>
  <p>What are the essential questions your learners should be able to discuss and reflect upon after this activity?
 </p>
